by Leskya » Mon Dec 28, 2020 1:38 pm

Arms and weapons trades are so common they have become socially normalised and treated no different than any other sales industry, seen as just another sector of the retail market. Synne Industries itself is responsible for around 40% of the global arms trade; however, domestically, the industry is highly competitive, with 'big businesses' only holding a collective 20% of market shares, with the remaining 80% being occupied by small, family-owned, and local stores. This is primarily due to a gentleman's agreement between Small and Big Business, stating that neither will interfere in the other's domestic market, thus granting a safe corner to the big corporations while maintaining a competitive market for the small guys.

Quite interested in hearing how that agreement is enforced, actually.

/stillme

OOC: It is indeed the case that "You are not real" is the opening line of the RSI Hub factbook—but that's just it: it's the very first words. Many consider it bad form to answer "what have you learnt" by repeating the first one or two lines of the first factbook nearly verbatim. It suggests a cursory read and little effort expended. Furthermore, I don't think the' RSI Factbook is really about solipsism; the first line is superficially solipsitic, but the content gets more into parallel dimensions and Extraspace.

Leskya wrote:Quite interested in hearing how that agreement is enforced, actually.

IC:

"Regretfully, I usually go straight to Politics when I login to the Leskya Portal. Ahh, how could I let my political appointment override my yearnings as a scholar of the humanities? So today, I decided to instead open the Culture page, and I read about Leskyan conflict resolution. Interestingly, Leskya claims that all conflict stems from personal schisms or emotional clashes, with none being about resource management or powergrabs. This is impressive—political theorists everywhere would give an arm and a leg to know how how you erased greed for power from your society. I had previously been concerned that statelessness would allow demagogues to use physical power to try and wield a commune as a weapon for themselves, but I am impressed to learn that Leskyans are beyond that type of behavior.

"Nevertheless, the Leskyan war game is a very curious tradition. Perhaps it is a consequence of growing up in Baizou, which has culturally eschewed martial culture and aesthetics ever since the Pacific War, but I could never imagine actually trying to draw blood as a sport. It just seems—for lack of a better word, bloodthirsty. And as a practical matter, think of the concussive or internal injuries that could happen before blood is drawn!"
—Ambassador Mizushima Miya

by Sanghyeok » Mon Dec 28, 2020 2:27 pm

Baizou's political parties are incredibly interesting- from their somewhat contradictory naming (Lotus "Conservatives" supporting some Labour policies, "Marxists" advocating for reform and not revolution, and "Libertarians" actually arguing against deregulation in some cases, "Power Party" advocating for disabled persons) to their number and rather diverse policies. Their governing "Grand Coalition", although grand in number of parties, is not so grand when considering they govern as a minority coalition holding 47% of seats in parliament (though they do have majority of seats in Council). Labour, despite being the largest party in above coalition, is actually not head of coalition, which belongs to the Marxist Party.
